  "What is thermal expansion in the context of sea level rise?": "",
  "The expansion of coastal land due to volcanic activity": "",
  "The increase in ocean volume as water expands when heated": "",
  "The widening of rivers from increased precipitation": "",
  "The growth of ice sheets during warm periods": "",
  "Thermal expansion occurs because water molecules move faster and spread apart as they warm, causing the ocean to physically expand in volume and contributing significantly to sea level rise.": "",
  "What is a proxy climate record?": "",
  "An indirect source of climate data derived from natural archives such as ice cores, tree rings, or corals": "",
  "A weather station located in a remote area": "",
  "A computer simulation of future climate conditions": "",
  "A substitute government agency that monitors weather": "",
  "Proxy climate records are natural archives that preserve indirect evidence of past climate conditions, including ice cores, tree rings, coral growth bands, and ocean sediment cores, allowing scientists to reconstruct climate history before instrumental records existed.": "",
  "What is Arctic amplification?": "",
  "The increase in Arctic wildlife populations due to warmer conditions": "",
  "The phenomenon where the Arctic warms 2-4 times faster than the global average": "",
  "The process of Arctic ice expanding during winter": "",
  "The amplification of radio signals near the North Pole": "",
  "Arctic amplification refers to the Arctic warming at 2-4 times the global average rate, primarily due to the ice-albedo feedback loop where melting ice exposes darker ocean water that absorbs more solar radiation.": "",
  "A marine biologist studying oyster farms notices that juvenile oysters have thinner, more fragile shells than those from 20 years ago. Which climate change evidence best explains this observation?": "",
  "Rising sea surface temperatures": "",
  "Ocean acidification reducing availability of carbonate ions for shell formation": "",
  "Overfishing of oyster predators": "",
  "Increased ocean salinity from evaporation": "",
  "Ocean acidification decreases the concentration of carbonate ions in seawater, making it harder for shell-building organisms like oysters to construct and maintain their calcium carbonate shells, resulting in thinner and more fragile shells.": "",
  "A city planner in Miami reviews data showing that sunny-day flooding has increased from 5 days per year in 2000 to 15 days per year currently. What evidence of climate change is this most directly linked to?": "",
  "Increased hurricane frequency": "",
  "Groundwater depletion causing land subsidence": "",
  "Accelerating sea level rise pushing high tides over infrastructure": "",
  "Changes in ocean current patterns": "",
  "Sunny-day or nuisance flooding occurs when high tides, elevated by sea level rise, push water over seawalls and through drainage systems even without storms, and this type of flooding is increasing rapidly in coastal cities.": "",
  "An ecologist in England documents that oak trees are leafing out 2 weeks earlier than they did in the 1970s, but the caterpillars that blue tit birds rely on to feed their young still peak at the original time. What climate evidence concept does this illustrate?": "",
  "Natural population cycles": "",
  "Invasive species introduction": "",
  "Habitat fragmentation": "",
  "Phenological mismatch caused by differential responses to warming": "",
  "This is a classic example of phenological mismatch, where different species in a food web respond to warming at different rates, causing ecological events like leaf-out, caterpillar emergence, and bird breeding to fall out of synchronization.": "",
  "A researcher drills an ice core in Antarctica and finds that CO2 levels in air bubbles from 10,000 years ago were 260 ppm, while current atmospheric CO2 is over 420 ppm. What conclusion can the researcher draw?": "",
  "CO2 naturally rises this high every 10,000 years": "",
  "Current CO2 levels far exceed natural variability seen in the ice core record": "",
  "The ice core data is unreliable at that depth": "",
  "CO2 levels have always been this high": "",
  "Ice core records show that atmospheric CO2 naturally fluctuated between about 180-280 ppm over hundreds of thousands of years; the current level above 420 ppm is unprecedented in at least 800,000 years, indicating human activities have dramatically altered atmospheric composition.": "",
  "A satellite analyst compares images of the Greenland Ice Sheet from 2000 and 2023, noting significantly more meltwater lakes on the surface in the recent image. Which two lines of climate evidence does this support?": "",
