  "A climate scientist presents data showing that without including human greenhouse gas emissions in models, the observed temperature increase since 1950 cannot be reproduced. What does this demonstrate?": "",
  "The warming is caused by urban heat island effects": "",
  "Climate models are unreliable": "",
  "Temperature records before 1950 are inaccurate": "",
  "Natural factors alone cannot explain observed warming; human influence is required": "",
  "When climate models are run with only natural forcings (solar variation, volcanic eruptions), they cannot reproduce the observed warming since 1950; only when human greenhouse gas emissions are included do the models match reality, providing strong evidence of human causation.": "",
  "A wine grower in Burgundy, France notes that grape harvests have moved earlier by about 2 weeks compared to the 1980s, and vineyards are now being planted in southern England. What type of climate evidence do these observations represent?": "",
  "Improved agricultural technology": "",
  "Phenological shifts and poleward expansion of suitable growing regions": "",
  "Natural 30-year climate oscillations": "",
  "Changes in soil chemistry": "",
  "Earlier grape harvests are a phenological indicator of warming temperatures, and the expansion of vineyards into previously too-cool regions like England demonstrates how warming is shifting the geographic range of suitable growing conditions poleward.": "",
  "For an AP APES free-response question, a student is asked to provide three independent lines of evidence for climate change. Which combination would receive full credit?": "",
  "Rising CO2 levels, rising methane levels, and rising N2O levels": "",
  "Temperature data from three different weather stations": "",
  "Ice core data, rising global temperatures, and declining Arctic sea ice": "",
  "Three different computer model projections": "",
  "The AP exam rewards students who cite multiple independent lines of evidence, such as paleoclimate records (ice cores), direct measurements (temperature), and physical observations (ice decline), rather than variations of a single data type.": ""
